	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				This is taken from a Fletching Guide i've come across:<BR>
----------------------------------------------<BR>
&quot;I will start with fletching arrows, as that is the main way to increase your level in fletching. By solely making arrows and increasing your level in fletching you also increase your ability to make more and more complex bows. One does not need to train in arrow making and seperately train in making bows.<BR>
<BR>
Introduction to Arrows:<BR>
<BR>
Arrows are made up of 4 basic parts: Points, Shafts, Nocks and either a Fletch or a Vane. Yes there are 5 different parts but only 4 of them are used at a time to make an arrow. At this point, I know of no way to fletch magical arrows or arrows with any other special attributes. Once you produce an arrow it will have four quailties, Arrow Type, Delay, Range and Damage. I have only seen 0 delay arrows and the Arrow type is not really that important. But, the range and damage of an arrow are very important.<BR>
<BR>
The final range at which an archer will be able to hit is the addition of the range of the bow and the range of the arrows that they are using. The same goes for the damage. The total possible damage is an addition of the arrow&#8217;s damage value and the bow&#8217;s damage value. But, as with any weapon, the damage actually imparted to the creature is not always the max of the weapon. The damage will depend on the creature, your level, your archery level and some other factors like STR and AGI.<BR>
<BR>
Beginning Arrow Making:<BR>
<BR>
STEP 1: You start to train in fletching by first purchasing a fletching kit and putting at least one practice point into the skill of fletching at your guild. One hint that I have heard of is that if your a level 20 character and you put one practice point into fletching, you will be made a level 20 fletcher. If you a level 10 character and you put one point into fletching you will be a level 10 fletcher. Optional things you can buy are the books on fletching and bowery that the merchants have. I have never been completely sure if these are needed or not. So buy them at your own descretion.<BR>
<BR>
And one other thing about using practice points, eventually you will reach a level 20 or 21 and the guildmaster will tell you that the remainder of your training must be done in the field, in other words, get out the fletching kit and fletch.<BR>
<BR>
The new flecthing kit has 8 slots while the older kit had 8. They only weigh .4 so I use them instead of backpacks. BUT, becareful not to hit the combine button, as you will combine everything in the backpack and will lose it all.<BR>
<BR>
STEP 2: Perchase 20 bundles of each of the 4 parts needed for making arrows from a vendor that sells arrow parts. Start with the cheapest: Field points, Wooden Shafts, Round Fletches and Large Nocks. These will cost about 5 to 6 copper for a bundle, and a bundle produces 5 arrows if your successful. So your first attempts will cost 4 X 5 or 6 copper, equaling 20 to 24 copper for 5 arrows. The only thing that will cause your cost of materials to go up or down is your personal CHR value and possibly how you&#8217;re greeted by the vendor. I have discovered that any level of CHR over 105 is wasted as you get no cheaper price with higher CHR, although I only tried CHR 115 and saw no increase. If you discover that a higher level of CHR gets you a cheaper price, please let me know. Later when you make arrows and sell them back to the merchants a high level of CHR will also get you the best price from the vendor.<BR>
STEP 3:  Now place one, and only one, of each of the 4 parts into the fletching kit and press the combine button.  As you fletch you will have two different things happen. The first is that you will either succeed and make 5 arrows or you will get a message saying that you lacked sufficient skill to make that item. If you get this message do not stop. Just keep trying. You will see this message a lot but keep making arrows. The other thing that might happen is that you might receive an increase in your level at fletching. It may seem funny but you can fail at making a bundle of arrows and still get an increase in your level at fletching.<BR>
<BR>
Each player has a certain level of INT and WIS. These values were determined at the time that you created your character. Each of these values affects your training in the following way. A higher WIS gives you a better chance of succeeding at making arrows instead of getting that message, &#8220;You lack the required skill&#8230;.&#8221;. A higher value of INT gives you a higher chance of getting an increase in your level at fletching. These attributes can be increased with equipment that has INT or WIS enchancements, like a sevants cap. Or, you can purchase INT and WIS increasing jewelery.<BR>
<BR>
STEP 4: Continue making arrows with these cheapest parts until you see the message that these arrows are now TRIVIAL.<BR>
<BR>
With these early arrows you can either use them or sell them to other archers. These early arrows will have a damage value of 1 and a range of 50. They are better than store bought arrows and can be sold for at least 1 silver per arrow, if not more. However, selling arrows can take a considerable amount of time and you may just prefer to use them to increase your archery level. If you are a class that cannot use a Bow, what the heck are you doing fletching. I know you can, but I ask, WHY?? A good archer is a better salesman of bows and arrows than a non-archer.<BR>
<BR>
Intermediate Fletching:<BR>
<BR>
Now that the Field Point, Wood Shaft, Round Fletch and Large Nock arrows are trivial, start making the same arrows but use the Medium Nocks instead of the Large Nocks. Through out your fletching training only one of the four components will be other than the 4 cheapest that you used for your first arrows. NEVER use TWO components that are more expensive than the first four that you used, while TRAINING.<BR>
<BR>
From the Medium Nock you should proceed through the following list of items one at a time progressing to the next and the next with each message that the current arrow is trivial. The full list is as follows:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Field Point, Wood Shaft, Round Fletch, Large Nock. These items make a 1 damage, 50 range arrow.<BR>
Medium Nock	gives the arrow 	+25 range<BR>
Parabolic Fletch	gives the arrow 	+50 range<BR>
Small Nock		gives the arrow 	+50 range<BR>
Bone shaft		gives the arrow 	+1 damage<BR>
Shield Fletch	gives the arrow 	-50 range and +1 damage<BR>
Hooked Point	gives the arrow 	+1 damage<BR>
Wood VANE	gives the arrow 	-25 range and +1 damage<BR>
Ceramic Shaft	gives the arrow 	+2 damage<BR>
Bone Vane		gives the arrow 	+25 range and +1 damage<BR>
Ceramic Vane	gives the arrow 	+2 damage<BR>
Steel Shaft		gives the arrow 	+3 damage<BR>
Bladed Point		gives the arrow 	+2 damage<BR>
<BR>
While your making arrow number 11 you should reach level 200 in fletching and I know of no one that has gone beyond level 200, as that is the supposed skill level cap for fletching. There is no level cap based on what level your character is as with other skills like 1HS or 2HB. So, a level 1 character could fletch until he became a level 200 fletcher. Hard to do with out cash but feasible.<BR>
<BR>
Advanced Fletching:<BR>
<BR>
This section is, probably, only for a master fletcher and above, although, it is not restricted to master fletchers only. A master fletcher is one that has a level of 100 or better. You should become a level 100 fletcher while doing arrow #7 in the list above. At this point you may have figured out that the descriptors given to each arrow component tells you what Range and/or Damage boost you should get when using that part to make an arrow. For example, using a Parabolic fletch and a small nock will give you a 150 range arrow that deals 1 damage. This comes from the fact that the normal arrow gives you a 50 range arrow that deals 1 damage and the addition of the parabolic fletch adds 50 to the range and the addition of the small nock adds another 50 to the range for a total range of 150.<BR>
<BR>
Once you have gotten the message about an arrow being trivial you should be able to use the part that is not one of: Field Point, Round Fletch, Wood Shaft or Large Nock, in any configuration along with other parts that have become trivial. In this way the fletcher can make some very useful and very saleable arrows that can help you earn plat to continue your fletching training.<BR>
<BR>
A peculiar point about arrows number 12 and 13 is that once I had reached fletching skill level 200 via arrow number 11, these higher numbered arrows were trivial but the number 11 arrow had still not become trivial. Also, number 11 arrows can be used to make plat. If your CHR is 105 and you deal with a merchant that gives you the best price, you will be able to sell the #11 arrows for a profit once your productivity is around and average of 85%. At fletching skill level 185 you should  have reached 85% productivity. Having a higher WIS will make your more productive earlier.<BR>
<BR>
Pricing Arrows:<BR>
<BR>
The ecomonmy of Norrath is a free enterprise one. You can sell your arrows for what ever you want. However, I would suggest pricing the arrows at from twice the materials cost to three times the materials cost. Once you fail on an expensve bow you will understand why I suggest this. Now that store bought arrows are not all that good the demand for Fletched arrows has gone up. Especially in the 150 range arrows.<BR>
<BR>
The arrows that I use and make for others, the most are the 1, 2, and 3 damage 150 range arrows.  If you take a close look at the table above you can figure out the components needed for these arrows. I will give you an example to help you along. A 150 range 1 damage arrow can be made with: Field Point, Wood Shaft, Round Fletch and Small Nock. So, as soon as the #4 arrow listed in the table above becomes trivial, these 150 range, 1 damage arrows should be easy to make. You will use the Parabolic Fletch from arrow #3 and the Small Nock from #4 arrow with the cheapest point and shaft, Field Point and Wood Shaft.&quot;<BR>
-----------------
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
